ehurst, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pashley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","nickname from Old French <i>passe lewe</i> ‘cross the water’, probably used for a seafarer or sailor. Compare   Parslow  . The name was sometimes treated like a Norman habitational name by adding the preposition <i>de</i>, although no such placename has been identified in Normandy or neighboring regions.","habitational name from Pashley in the parish of Ticehurst, Sussex. The placename is from Old English <i>Pæcces</i> + <i>lēah</i> ‘Pæcca's wood or clearing’. A district of Eastbourne, Sussex, bearing this name derives it from the surname; a family called Pashley had moved there from Ticehurst by the later part of the 13th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Parslow","meanings":["English: Anglicized form of the Old French nickname <i>passe lewe</i> ‘cross the water’; see   Pashley  ."]},{"name":"Parsley","meanings":["English: variant of   Pashley  ."]},{"name":"Passley","meanings":["English: variant of   Pashley  ."]},{"name":"Pasley","meanings":["English: variant of   Pashley  .","Scottish: variant of   Paisley  . Black suggests also that some examples of <i>Pasley</i> and <i>Paisley</i> may be derived from a place known as Pasley or Howpasley, in the Borders region.","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Pasler</b>, a variant of   Basler  , or of <b>Pässler</b>, an occupational name, from an agent derivative of <i>basteln</i> ‘to do handicraft’."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Pashley de Passele was born in 1341, in Smeeth, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert I Pashley Lord of Thevegate, was 25 and his mother, Joan de Etchingham, was 22. He married Anne Howard before October 1366, in Wiggenhall St Peter, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1397, in Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1341–1397":"1341–1397","1370–1407":"1370–1407","1317–1362":"1317–1362","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1397":"1397","1320":"1320","1341":"1341","1362":"1362","1370":"1370","1407":"1407","before October 1366":"enne oktoobrit 1366","1317":"1317","Smeeth, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Smeeth, Kent, In